<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-151-218 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 777 994</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  May 20 1991 v2 n52 p40(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple System 7: Microsoft announces full support.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   System 7.0 (Operating system) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentCompatible SoftwareSoftware DesignSoftware PublishersOperating Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft Corp. Monday unveiled plans for implementing System 7 technologyinto all its Apple Macintosh applications.andM;At the System 7 announcement, Bill Gates stated that all Microsoftapplications will fully implement System 7 technology within 12 months.andO;Technology such as Publish andamp; Subscribe, Apple events, Balloon Help, virtualmemory and TrueType scalable font technology will be implemented throughoutthe product line.andM;&quot;System 7 allows us to create better Macintosh applications,&quot; stated MikeMaples, vice president of applications software at Microsoft.andP;  &quot;Capabilitiesthat we used to build into our applications, such as `warm links,' are nowsupported in System 7, allowing us to break new ground by adding even more ofthe functionality requested by users.&quot;andM;At the announcement, Microsoft highlighted Microsoft Excel version 3.0 forthe Macintosh as an example of how System 7 technology will be implementedacross the product line.andP;  Under System 7, Microsoft Excel users can publishworksheets and charts to other applications and subscribe to editionspublished by other applications.andP;  Microsoft Excel for the Macintosh version3.0 is currently shipping.andM;Balloon Help lets users of Microsoft Excel get a quick overview of menucommands or commands provided on the Toolbar.andP;  This is especially useful forusers who are new to Microsoft Excel.andM;Microsoft Excel version 3.0 also takes advantage of virtual memory andTrueType, the new scalable font technology.andP;  In addition, Microsoft Excelwill use the new DataAccess Manager which provides enhanced tools foraccessing remote databases.andM;In addition to supporting Apple's required set of Apple events, Microsoftwill support a subsequent set of events that will facilitate real-timesharing of data.andP;  This added support will allow users to extend the waysapplications work together.andO;</TEXT></DOC>